Java CC Monthly Newsletter - August 2019

The most important news about Java in August gathered in a single post are already here! In case you have missed something, here is a chance to catch up.

 
 

Steaming Cup of Coffee

 
 
 
 
 
 

Work begins on Java 14

Java 13 is still not released, but work has already begun on its successor, Java 14. 
There is one JEP targeted for JDK 14 so far, which would upgrade Javas mapped byte buffers to support non-volatile memory. 
Stay tuned for more!

 
 
 
 
 

Jakarta EE 8 Is Sprinting Towards an Exciting Future for Enterprise Java

After what seemed like an eternity, the time has finally come the long awaited first release of Jakarta EE is now officially in the hands of the public.
Now the community can start hoping for faster development of the platform.

 
 
 
 

There Is Always More to Learn

 
 
 
 
 

Don't Get Locked Up into Avoiding Lock-In

A significant share of architectural energy is spent on reducing or avoiding lock-in as architecture is meant to give us options and lock-in does the opposite.
However, lock-in isn't a simple true-or-false matter: avoiding being locked into one aspect often locks you into another.
Time to have a closer look at lock-in, so you don't get locked up into avoiding it!

 
 
 
 
 
 

Hacking Enums Revisited

In this post you will see how you could dynamically add new enums and also rewire affected switch statements even after JDK12. 
As a useful side effect you will understand how enums work under the hood.
Happy reading (hacking)!

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Tools to Keep JavaDoc Up-To-Date

There are many projects where the documentation is not up-to-date. It is easy to forget to change the documentation after the code was changed.
In this article, Peter Verhas will show you an example, how to ease the process and ensure that the documentation is at least more up-to-date.

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Building A Spelling Correction System in Java

See how you can build your own Spelling Correction System in Java by relying on two fundamental and old concepts: the Soundex Algorithm and Levenshtein Distance to provide suggestions for correction of the misspelled word.

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Scaling up Performance Benchmarking

In this talk, Anil Kumar and Monica Beckwith share application architecture decisions, observations points, etc. which can be applied when architecting, deploying and analyzing real production applications. They also share how application level, as well as system level metrics, change for various application architecture decisions as well as high-level JVM analysis to correlate tail latencies.

 
 
 
 
 

Bean Validation Anti-Patterns

Bean Validation is the de-facto standard for implementing validation logic in the Java ecosystem and its a great tool to have around.
However, there are usages of it that could be considered harmful. Read more to find out how to improve the maintainability of your validations by avoiding some antipatterns. 

 
 
 
 
 

Using the Optimal Query Approach and Projection for JPA and Hibernate

Using JPA and Hibernate, you can choose between various ways to query your data, and each of them supports one or more kinds of projections. But which one fits your use case? And which one should you avoid if you want to optimize your persistence layer for performance?

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Cellery: A Code-First Approach to Deploy Applications on Kubernetes

Cell-Based Architecture, a microservice architecture pattern, introduced the concept of reusable building blocks called cells intended for grouping services (and other components) into easily manageable and deployable units.
Cellery is a combination of an SDK, a runtime, and a management framework can help you applying this patterns on top of Kubernetes.

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Custom Error Handling in REST Controllers with Spring Boot

This guide shows you how to implement custom error handling in Spring Boot. You will see in action not only the well-known ControllerAdvice and ExceptionHandler annotations but also DefaultErrorAttributes and ErrorController to make your custom error attributes uniform and consistent.

 
 
 
 
 
 

Quick Guide to Building a Spring Boot Starter 

In Spring Boot, there is a solution to help implement and reuse cross-cutting concerns across every Spring Boot application were building, called starter.
In this article, you will see it in action for building a starter to easily send and receive Events over an imaginary central messaging infrastructure.

 
 
 
 
 

Know for Sure with Property-Based Testing

Writing unit tests with a tool such as JUnit is an essential technique to ensure the quality of your code. However, when a function requires many test cases to check for all potential problems, testing becomes burdensome and error-prone. Property-based testing (PBT) can rescue and relieve you from writing dozens of test cases.

 
 
 
 
 

Jabel Brings Post-Java 8 Features to Java 8 Users

Do you want to stay on Java 8 while taking advantage of the latest Java syntax and features?
A tool called Jabel enables this because, as its GitHub page states, life is too short to wait for your users to upgrade their Java.

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

On the Road to Mastery

 
 
 
 

The Difference Between Collection.stream().forEach() and Collection.forEach()

There are several options to iterate over a collection in Java. In this short tutorial, you can look at two similar looking approaches Collection.stream().forEach() and Collection.forEach(). In most cases, both will yield the same results, however, there are some subtle differences you will look at.

 
 
 
 

Class Loaders in Java 

Class loaders are responsible for loading Java classes during runtime dynamically to the JVM.
In this tutorial, you are going to learn about different types of built-in class loaders, how they work and an introduction to an own custom implementation.
